Multi-tenancy is an important architectural pattern in cloud-native systems, enabling e cient resource sharing while maintaining isolation between tenants. Multi-tenancy can be implemented on many di erent levels of modern cloud deployments. Mature database management systems such as PostgreSQL supports di erent multi-tenancy models, including schema-per-tenant, database-per-tenant, and, in containerized environments, container-per-tenant. In this paper, we present a comparative study of these multi-tenancy strategies, focusing on performance evaluation and resource e ciency. We evaluate each model in PostgreSQL using industry-standard TPC-C (transactional) and TPC-H (analytical) benchmarks deployed in a dockerized microservice architecture orchestrated by Kubernetes, with each tenant itself encapsulated in a dedicated container. The results highlight the trade-o s among strict isolation, performance, and resource e ciency. For CPU-intensive workloads such as TPC-C, a container-per-tenant approach is the most bene cial. In contrast, for memory-intensive workloads like TPC-H, it is the least e cient.


